</p>

<p>
Men kill each other at greater distances, it is true=E2=80=94but killing is=
 a
constant factor in all battles. The difference between =E2=80=9Cnow and
then=E2=80=9D lies in this, that, thanks to the enormous increase in range =
(the
essential feature in modern armaments), it is possible to concentrate by
surprise, on any chosen spot, a man-killing power fully twentyfold greater =
than
was conceivable in the days of Waterloo; and whereas in Napoleon=E2=80=99s =
time
this concentration of man-killing power (which in his hands took the form o=
f
the great case-shot attack) depended almost entirely on the shape and condi=
tion
of the ground, which might or might not be favourable, nowadays such
