rising ground, a house, or a tree=E2=80=94a sure sign of increasing danger.=
 Grape
rattles on the roofs of the houses and in the fields; cannon balls howl ove=
r
us, and plough the air in all directions, and soon there is a frequent
whistling of musket balls. A step farther towards the troops, to that sturd=
y
infantry which for hours has maintained its firmness under this heavy fire;
here the air is filled with the hissing of balls which announce their proxi=
mity
by a short sharp noise as they pass within an inch of the ear, the head, or=
