results. The subjects which in one respect belong to the fighting itself ar=
e
<i>marches, camps</i>, and <i>cantonments</i>, for they suppose so many dif=
ferent situations
of troops, and where troops are supposed there the idea of the combat must
always be present.
</p>

<p>
The other subjects, which only belong to the maintenance, are <i>subsistenc=
e, care
of the sick</i>, the <i>supply and repair of arms and equipment</i>.
</p>

<p>
Marches are quite identical with the use of the troops. The act of marching=
