on that account exclusively a subject of strategy, for as the armed force w=
hich
executes it may be involved in a possible combat at any moment, therefore i=
ts
execution stands also under tactical as well as strategic rules. If we
prescribe to a column its route on a particular side of a river or of a bra=
nch
of a mountain, then that is a strategic measure, for it contains the intent=
ion
of fighting on that particular side of the hill or river in preference to t=
he
other, in case a combat should be necessary during the march.
</p>

<p>
But if a column, instead of following the road through a valley, marches al=
