<p>
If criticism dispenses praise or censure, it should seek to place itself as
nearly as possible at the same point of view as the person acting, that is =
to
say, to collect all he knew and all the motives on which he acted, and, on =
the
other hand, to leave out of the consideration all that the person acting co=
uld
not or did not know, and above all, the result. But this is only an object =
