</p>

<p>
In War more than anywhere else in the world things happen differently to wh=
at
we had expected, and look differently when near, to what they did at a
distance. With what serenity the architect can watch his work gradually ris=
ing
and growing into his plan. The doctor although much more at the mercy of
mysterious agencies and chances than the architect, still knows enough of t=
he
forms and effects of his means. In War, on the other hand, the Commander of=
 an
immense whole finds himself in a constant whirlpool of false and true
