(*) Railways, steamships, and telegraphs have, however, enormously modified=
 the
relative importance and practicability of surprise. (EDITOR.)
</p>

<p>
On the other hand, with things which can be done in a day or two, a surpris=
e is
much more conceivable, and, therefore, also it is often not difficult thus =
to
gain a march upon the enemy, and thereby a position, a point of country, a
road, &amp;c. But it is evident that what surprise gains in this way in eas=
