</p>

<p>
An excess of cavalry can certainly never be looked upon as a direct diminut=
ion
of the combatant force, as an organic disproportion, but it may certainly b=
e so
indirectly, on account of the difficulty of feeding that arm, and also if w=
e
reflect that instead of a surplus of 10,000 horsemen not required we might =
have
50,000 infantry.
</p>

<p>
These peculiarities arising from the preponderance of one arm are the more
