<p>
We here mean the march of a number of whole divisions at once, from one cam=
p to
another, for that is the usual form of marches made on a theatre of war. Wh=
en
several divisions are to march in one column, the first division to move is
assembled and marched off earlier than the rest, and therefore arrives at i=
ts
camping ground so much the sooner. At the same time this difference can sti=
ll
never amount to the whole time, which corresponds to the depth of a divisio=
n on
the line of march, and which is so well expressed in French, as the time it
requires for its <i>d=C3=A9coulement</i> (running down). The soldier is, th=
erefore,
saved very little fatigue in this way, and every march is very much lengthe=
ned
in duration in proportion as the number of troops to be moved increases. To
assemble and march off the different brigades of a division, in like manner=
