</p>

<p>
However, it is not our intention to enter into details=E2=80=94into the who=
le
machinery of commissariat and army subsistence; we have only results in vie=
w.
</p>

<p>
The result to be derived from a common-sense view of all the circumstances =
in
general, and the view which the experience of the wars since the French
revolution tends to confirm is,=E2=80=94that even the largest army, if it c=
arries
with it provisions for a few days, may undoubtedly be subsisted by
contributions which, commencing at the moment of entering a country, affect=
