try in
which it is operating contributing, as a rule, nothing towards its support.
</p>

<p>
The great difference consists in two things,=E2=80=94namely, the employment=
 of
the transport of the country, and its ovens. In this way, that enormous bur=
den
of any army, that incubus which is always destroying its own work, a milita=
ry
transport train, is almost got rid of.
</p>

<p>
It is true that even now no army can do entirely without some subsistence
