eat
through an enemy=E2=80=99s country. In such a case many of the inconvenienc=
es
connected with subsistence meet together. The operation is one of a continu=
ous
nature, generally carried on without a halt worth speaking of; there is,
therefore, no time to procure provisions; the circumstances under which the
operation commences are generally unfavourable, it is therefore necessary t=
o
keep the troops in masses, and a dispersion in cantonments, or even any
