imperative. Thus from this point of view the modern method of carrying on w=
ar
has a tendency to shorten the duration of wars.
</p>

<p>
At the same time we shall not positively deny the possibility of the old sy=
stem
of subsistence reappearing in future wars; it will perhaps be resorted to b=
y
belligerents hereafter, where the nature of their mutual relations urge the=
m to
it, and circumstances are favourable to its adoption; but we can never perc=
eive
in that system a natural organisation; it is much rather an abnormal growth
permitted by circumstances, but which can never spring from war in its true
sense. Still less can we consider that form or system as any improvement in=
