it does so with that portion immediately in its rear, and which is conseque=
ntly
covered by its position. In this portion of the country then, as far as
necessary, special dep=C3=B4ts of provisions are formed, and arrangements a=
re made
for regularly forwarding reinforcements and supplies. This strip of territo=
ry
is therefore the foundation of the army and of all its undertakings, and th=
e
two must be regarded as forming in connection only one whole. If the suppli=
