ved
or collected. These three things are separated in space, and cannot be
collected into one whole, and least of all can we substitute for them a lin=
e
which is to represent the width of the base, a line which is generally imag=
ined
in a manner perfectly arbitrary, either from one fortress to another or fro=
m
one capital of a province to another, or along a political boundary of a
country. Neither can we determine precisely the mutual relation of these th=
ree
steps in the formation of a base, for in reality they blend themselves with
each other always more or less. In one case the surrounding country affords
