</p>

<p>
When once arrangements are made within a certain radius to provide the mean=
s of
subsisting an army and keeping it complete in every respect, and with a vie=
w to
operations in a certain direction, then, even in our own country, this dist=
rict
only is to be regarded as the base of the army; and as any alteration of a =
base
requires time and labour, therefore an army cannot change its base every da=
y,
even in its own country, and this again limits it always more or less in th=
e
direction of its operations. If, then, in operating against an enemy=E2=80=
=99s
country we take the whole line of our own frontier, where it forms a bounda=
