given his wings secure him from any sudden attack from several quarters; th=
e
covered ground which he has chosen for his masses makes the enemy cautious,
indeed timid, and affords the defensive the means of diminishing by partial=
 and
successful attacks the general backward movement which goes on as the comba=
t
becomes gradually concentrated within narrower limits. The defender therefo=
re
casts a contented look at the battle as it burns in a moderate blaze before
him;=E2=80=94but he does not reckon that his resistance in front can last f=
or
ever;=E2=80=94he does not think his flanks impregnable;=E2=80=94he does not=
