of gravity of the battle, now only resting on a point, make the whole recoi=
l.
</p>

<p>
This is the normal idea which we have formed of a defensive battle, based o=
n
the tactics of the present day. In this battle the general turning movement
made by the assailant in order to assist his attack, and at the same time w=
ith
a view to make the results of victory more complete, is replied to by a par=
tial
turning movement on the part of the defensive, that is, by the turning of t=
hat
part of the assailant=E2=80=99s force used by him in the attempt to turn. T=
his
partial movement may be supposed sufficient to destroy the effect of the
enemy=E2=80=99s attempt, but it cannot lead to a like general enveloping of=
