from a common centre, give that point and the army placed there such streng=
th,
that, if other conditions allowed of it, in some measure one would be very =
much
tempted to form such a strategic bastion.
</p>

<p>
The last point concerns the other geographical properties of the points to =
be
chosen. That fortresses on the sea, on streams and great rivers, and in
mountains, are doubly effective, has been already stated to be one of the
principal considerations; but there are a number of other points in connect=
ion
with fortresses to which regard must be paid.
</p>

<p>
If a fortress cannot lie on the river itself, it is better not to place it
