ing
it, and thus secures to that force the power of keeping the field, that is =
to
say, <i>maintaining itself in the country</i>. Such a camp cannot be
<i>turned</i>, that is, cannot be attacked in flank or rear by reason of th=
ose
parts being weaker than its front, for it can show front in all directions,=
