given to a small post planted on a point difficult of access, was still mor=
e
suited to lead to an exaggerated idea of the strength of mountain defences.=
 The
opinion arose that it was only necessary to multiply such a post by a certa=
in
number to make an army out of a battalion, a chain of mountains out of a
mountain.
</p>

<p>
It is undeniable that a small post acquires an extraordinary strength by
selecting a good position in a mountainous country. A small detatchment, wh=
ich
would be driven off in the level country by a couple of squadrons, and thin=
k
itself lucky to save itself from rout or capture by a hasty retreat, can in=
