followed that the assailant, being the last to form his line of battle,
naturally adapted it to the order of battle adopted by the enemy, without t=
he
latter being able in turn to modify his in accordance. The attack thus acqu=
ired
a general superiority, and the defensive had no other means of reinstating =
the
balance than that of seeking protection from the impediments of ground, and=
