a
paralysing principle. There are two reasons for this: first, want of roads
affording means of rapidly moving in all directions, from the rear towards =
the
front, and even the sudden tactical attack is hampered by the unevenness of
ground; secondly, a free view over the country, and the enemy=E2=80=99s mov=
ements
is not to be had. The ground in mountains, therefore, ensures in this case =
to
the enemy the same advantages which it gave to us in the front, and deadens=
