my
would occupy.
</p>

<p>
What sections of territory the advancing foe will occupy right and left of =
his
course, can with tolerable accuracy be discerned by the point of assembly o=
f,
and directions given to, his forces, by the situation of his own provinces,
fortresses, etc., in respect to our own. To place troops in those districts=
 of
territory which he will in all probability leave unoccupied, would be dange=
rous
waste of our forces. But now whether <i>by any disposition of our forces we
