here, for we look upon a people=E2=80=99s war merely as a means of fighting=
,
therefore, in its connection with the enemy; but with regard to the latter
point, we must observe that a people=E2=80=99s war in general is to be rega=
rded
as a consequence of the outburst which the military element in our day has =
made
through its old formal limits; as an expansion and strengthening of the who=
le
fermentation-process which we call war. The requisition system, the immense
