force, in order to withdraw these provinces entirely from his influence. Wh=
ere
no enemy is to be found, there is no want of courage to oppose him, and at =
the
example thus given, the mass of the neighboring population gradually takes
fire. Thus the fire spreads as it does in heather, and reaching at last tha=
t
part of the surface of the soil on which the aggressor is based, it seizes =
his
lines of communication and preys upon the vital thread by which his existen=
ce
is supported. For although we entertain no exaggerated ideas of the omnipot=
ence
of a people=E2=80=99s war, such as that it is an inexhaustible, unconquerab=
le
element, over which the mere force of an army has as little control as the
human will has over the wind or the rain; in short, although our opinion is=
