ts,
courage rises, the love of fighting gains strength, and the intensity of th=
is
struggle increases until the crisis approaches which is to decide the issue=
.
</p>

<p>
According to our idea of a people=E2=80=99s war, it should, like a kind of
nebulous vapoury essence, never condense into a solid body; otherwise the e=
nemy
sends an adequate force against this core, crushes it, and makes a great ma=
ny
prisoners; their courage sinks; every one thinks the main question is decid=
ed,
any further effort useless, and the arms fall from the hands of the people.
Still, however, on the other hand, it is necessary that this mist should
