tenacity if the combat is prolonged. Further, the defeat and dispersion of =
a
body of national levies is of no material consequence, as they lay their
account with that, but a body of this description must not be broken up by
losses in killed, wounded, and prisoners; a defeat of that kind would soon =
cool
their ardour. But both these peculiarities are entirely opposed to the natu=
re
of a tactical defensive. In the defensive combat a persistent slow systemat=
ic
action is required, and great risks must be run; a mere attempt, from which=
