</p>

<p>
If the victorious enemy is engaged in siege works, if he has left strong
garrisons behind him everywhere to secure his communications, or detached c=
orps
to make himself elbow-room, and to keep the adjacent provinces in subjectio=
n,
if he is already weakened by his various losses in active means and materia=
l of
war, then the moment is arrived when the defensive army should again enter =
the
lists, and by a well-directed blow make the assailant stagger in his
disadvantageous position.
</p>

