head quarters at Wilna there was a party of men of high mark who insisted o=
n a
battle on the frontier, in order that no hostile foot should tread on Russi=
an
ground with impunity. That this battle on the frontier <i>might</i> be lost=
,
nay, that it <i>would</i> be lost, these men certainly admitted; for althou=
gh
they did not know that there would be 300,000 French to meet 80,000 Russian=
s,
still they knew that the enemy was considerably superior in numbers. The ch=
