<p>
The occupation of an undefended strip of territory, therefore, in addition =
to
the value which it has as a direct fulfilment of the end, may also reckon a=
s a
destruction of the enemy=E2=80=99s force as well. The man=C5=93uvring, so a=
s to draw
an enemy out of a district of country which he has occupied, is somewhat
similar, and must, therefore, only be looked at from the same point of view=
,
and not as a success of arms, properly speaking=E2=80=94These means are gen=
erally
estimated at more than they are worth=E2=80=94they have seldom the value of=
